<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hollywood Memorabilia Sells: The Jewish marriage certificate of Marilyn Monroe 
and Arthur Miller was sold Thursday in London for $13,700, Christie's 
auctioneers said. The ketubah, a framed marriage certificate with a decorated 
border in the style of a medieval manuscript, was sold by the executors of 
Monroe's estate and bought by an unidentified American. Indiana Jones' kangaroo 
hide bullwhip sold for $24,300 -- more than double its estimate -- to the owner 
of Paris' City Rock Cafe. CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA122190-0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 325332 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 21, 1990, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
227 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP ALBUM CHART; 
</P>
<P>
SELLING TO THE EXTREME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vanilla Ice's "To the Extreme" is one of the fastest-selling albums in many 
years. Though out less about four months, it's already sold more than 5 million 
units and is still going strong. 
</P>
<P>
For the last eight weeks, it's been the No. 1 album on the Billboard magazine 
pop chart. M.C. Hammer's "Please Hammer Don't Hurt 'em" -- a fixture at No.2 
after months on top -- is still a big seller, but it's just not selling at the 
phenomenal rate of Ice. The Simpsons' album, "The Simpsons Sing the Blues," is 
the hot newcomer, barreling up to No. 10 in just two weeks. Madonna's "Justify 
My Love" moved up to No. 1 on the pop singles chart. 
</P>
<P>
* This album of remixed versions of New Kids' hits is shooting up the chart, 
jumping from No. 30 to No. 19. It won't be as popular as the group's Christmas 
album last year, but it may make the Top 10. 
</P>
