<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ARTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEA Grants Awarded: The National Endowment for the Arts announced Thursday it 
is awarding $15.6 million in long-term grants to support "exciting, innovative 
and far-reaching" projects by 37 arts organizations from Hanover, N.H., to 
Tacoma, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
Million-dollar grants were awarded to New York choreographer Merce Cunningham, 
public television's "American Playhouse" series and the Houston Grand Opera. 
The smallest grant, $50,000, went to public radio station KLON-FM in Long 
Beach. New York City arts organizations were the biggest winners, with nine 
grants totaling $4,655,000. The next highest total, six grants worth 
$2,660,000, went to San Francisco, including an $850,000 award to the Fine Arts 
Museums to seismically reinforce the California Palace of the Legion of Honor. 
CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
