<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
PRICES INFLATE JAPANESE ASSETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Service 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paced by soaring land and stock prices, Japan's national assets jumped 14.4% in 
1989 to $52.7 trillion, far exceeding the nation's gross national product, the 
Economic Planning Agency reported today. 
</P>
<P>
Japan's GNP grew 7.2% to $3.12 trillion in fiscal 1989 ended last March 31. 
</P>
<P>
The agency said Japan's gross domestic product at the end of calendar 1989 
stood at $22.1 billion, ranking second after the United States among member 
countries of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development. 
</P>
<P>
Japan's per capita gross domestic product stood at $23,296, ranking second 
after Switzerland with $26,104. 
</P>
<P>
Finland was third with $23,196, followed by Sweden with $22,443, Norway with 
$21,334 and the United States with $20,768, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
