292 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: JAPANESE ELECTRONICS COMPANIES PLUG INTO HOLLYWOOD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PEOPLE ARE talking about two Hollywood stories, one in the Wall Street Journal, 
the other in M Inc. Both deal with Sony of Japan's U.S. company, Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
The WSJ asks if Columbia's Tri-Star production of "Hook" (the tale of Peter Pan 
grown up) will fly. 
</P>
<P>
CAA, which represents Steve Spielberg, Dustin Hoffman and Robin Williams, the 
principals, made a deal that means its clients will get roughly 40% of the 
gross of this movie plus a percentage of all the merchandising as well. "Hook" 
will have to sell $125 million worth of tickets to break even. 
</P>
<P>
Why did Tri-Star give away the store on this one, set for Christmas release in 
1991? Because Tri-Star's dynamic Mike Medavoy believes "everyone is going to 
make money." Reporter Laura Landro quotes another exec who says: "They made a 
strategic decision to show that they could be in business with a director and 
stars of this caliber, no matter what the cost. . . . But it could give them 
enormous credibility." 
</P>
<P>
Then, there is M's article by Russell Miller, "Star Struck! Has Hollywood 
Hustled the Japanese?" There is some necessary rehash here in the story, the 
tale of how Jon Peters and Peter Guber won the top spot to run Columbia, and 
the magazine comments, "The big electronics companies are banking on movies to 
sell their hardware. What they didn't count on were the spending habits of guys 
like Guber and Peters." 
</P>
<P>
Russell says Guber and Peters have gone underground. Knowing their Sony bosses 
don't like all the publicity, "two of the fastest talkers in Hollywood are 
suddenly overcome by shyness and a desire to avoid the limelight. 
</P>
<P>
All requests for interviews are refused, it being 'too premature' for them to 
speak about their plans. Family and friends are warned not to speak." 
</P>
</TEXT>
